What happens when you type https://www.google.com in your browser and press Enter.
Lucy Ann Santiago Lizasoain
Lucy Ann Santiago Lizasoain 
Software Engineer(aspiring) at Holberton Coding School / Licensed Chemist | Analytical Chemistry, Data Analysis /MS Cybersecurity and IT at Atlantis University


May 18, 2025
by Lucy Ann Santiago Lizasoain

Abstract
This document explores the technical journey that occurs when a user enters "google.com" into a web browser. It highlights the various cybersecurity steps that take place to ensure a secure connection, protect user data, and maintain the integrity of the website. Understanding these processes is crucial for appreciating the importance of cybersecurity in our daily online interactions.

Steps Involved When Accessing Google.com
DNS Resolution:

When "google.com" is entered, the browser first checks its cache to see if it has the IP address stored. If not, it sends a request to a Domain Name System (DNS) server to resolve the domain name into an IP address. This is the address of the server hosting Google.

Establishing a Connection:

Once the IP address is obtained, the browser initiates a connection to the server using the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP). This involves a three-way handshake to establish a reliable connection.

TLS Handshake:

If the connection is secure (which it typically is for Google), a Transport Layer Security (TLS) handshake occurs. This step is crucial for encrypting the data exchanged between the user and the server. During this handshake, the browser and server agree on encryption methods and exchange certificates to verify each other's identities.

Sending the HTTP Request:

After the secure connection is established, the browser sends an HTTP request to the Google server, asking for the webpage. This request includes various headers that provide information about the browser and the type of content it can accept.

Server Response:

The Google server processes the request and sends back an HTTP response, which includes the requested webpage data. This response may also contain additional security headers, such as Content Security Policy (CSP) and X-Content-Type-Options, to protect against various types of attacks.

Rendering the Page:

The browser receives the response and begins rendering the webpage. This involves interpreting HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to display the content correctly. During this process, the browser may make additional requests for resources like images, scripts, and stylesheets.

Security Measures:

Throughout this entire process, various cybersecurity measures are in place:

 Encryption: TLS ensures that data is encrypted during transmission, preventing eavesdropping.

 Authentication: Certificates verify the identity of the server, ensuring that users are connecting to the legitimate Google site.

 Content Security Policies: These policies help prevent cross-site scripting (XSS) and other injection attacks by controlling which resources can be loaded.

 Regular Security Updates: Both browsers and servers are regularly updated to patch vulnerabilities and enhance security.

User Interaction:

Once the page is fully loaded, users can interact with it. Any data entered, such as search queries or personal information, is again protected by encryption and other security measures.

Conclusion
The process of accessing a website like Google.com involves multiple steps that prioritize user security and data integrity. From DNS resolution to secure connections and data encryption, cybersecurity plays a vital role in ensuring a safe browsing experience. Understanding these processes helps users appreciate the complexities of web interactions and the importance of cybersecurity in our digital lives.

